&gt; Andrew McDonagh wrote:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; I use the following pattern...
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; public void testVariousParams() {
&gt; &gt;       paramTest(&quot;a param&quot;;
&gt; &gt;       paramTest(&quot;second test param&quot;);
&gt; &gt;       ....
&gt; &gt; }
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; private void paramTest(String expectedValue) {
&gt; &gt;       Something something = new Something();
&gt; &gt;       assertEquals(&quot;didn&#39;t work&quot;, expectedvalue, something.getValue());
&gt; &gt; }
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; The only issue is that the private test case methods cannot be named
&gt; &gt; test**** as the JUnit framework moans about them being private or having
&gt; &gt; params.
&gt;
&gt; Extract testVariousParams() into the suite() method and you have the
&gt; beginnings of the Parameterized Test Case pattern. The above is exactly
&gt; how I used to do it.
